blog.title: (lives between pages)
blog.description: Holistic Writer / INTJ / Chaotic Good / Slytherin / Jewish / QIA-spec in LGBTQIA+ / autistic rabblerouser / still in my 30s / they-pronouns. Emma Goldman stan. Survivor of traumas I only discuss when relevant. Contains black tea, insomnia, poetry, & fic—but mostly just fic. If you're looking for CoT 'Verse and the rest of my Good Omens fic, you can find it here. As of 2013, all of my old LJ-era fanfiction has been uploaded to AO3. I'm the nutter behind @ask-agnes-nutter, so feel free to send asks. I moderate for the largest, most active GO Discord server, The Ritz; if you would like an invite, please DM me. You can pester me; I strongly encourage anons, because I know not everyone finds sending asks easy. If you want to know where to find my published work, email me on irisbleufic@gmail.com or send a DM. If you make art based on my writing, podfic my stories, or do anything you want me to see, tag it #irisbleufic. I won’t tell folks they shouldn't follow, but there's complex content here. I tag thoroughly. You can ko-fi me if you wish.

Crowley makes examples of his plants that don’t do well and all, but he’s really just transfering them to like a greenhouse because they’re more delicate and he can take gentler care of them there.

summary: Good Omens: The Nice and Accurate Prophecies of Agnes Nutter, Witch by Terry Pratchett & Neil Gaiman
title: Good Omens: The Nice and Accurate Prophecies of Agnes Nutter, Witch by Terry Pratchett & Neil Gaiman
body:
Honestly, where was this book my whole life. I have seen the trailer for the series and wanted to watch it straight away and then I learned it’s based on a book by two authors, one that absolutely love and one that I heard only great things about (RIP Sir Terry Pratchett), so I knew I need to read this. I was a little afraid, as I always am, when reading an old work of someone I love newer ones; and when reading collaborations (this has both so I double so).
Fortunately this book doesn’t disappoint. I expected that much from Neil Gaiman and will definitely check out more by Sir Terry Pratchett.

I really liked the unique combination of writing styles and the characters were phenomenal, I liked how even the demons weren’t really portrayed as villains, just as someone that is doing their job without really questioning if its right to do so, even though some of them enjoyed doing it more than others. But my absolute favourite characters is Adam and was, for some reason, tearing up at the end. And obviously the main pair, Crowley and Aziraphale.

The whole book is really funny, but it has its moments where it shows it was written in the ‘90. Let’s just say, some of the jokes didn’t age as well as others. But the bits with Elvis were great.

This book quickly became one of my favourites and now I’m afraid that won’t like the adaptation, story of my life.
